The paper deals with the problem of maximizing submodular functions in a distributed setting, which is a topic that falls under the category of game theory (cs.GT), distributed computing (cs.DC), machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and social and information networks (cs.SI). The paper discusses the impact of limited information on the performance of a greedy algorithm, which is a problem that is relevant to all of these sub-categories. However, since the paper focuses on the design and analysis of algorithms, it is less likely to belong to the sub-categories of computer vision (cs.CV) or human-computer interaction (cs.HC), which are more concerned with applications and user interfaces.
